Trim the @carrot{1}, halve lengthways, then thinly slice (no need to peel). Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{}(stalks and all).

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain and rinse the @brown lentils{1%can} in a #sieve{}.

Mix the @honey{15%g} and half the @wholegrain mustard{17%g} in a #bowl{}.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Season the @British pork loin steaks{2} with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Once hot, add the pork steaks. Cook until browned, ~{2-3%minutes} on each side.

Reduce the heat to medium and fry for an additional ~{6-8%minutes}, turning every couple of mins.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While the pork cooks, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a medium frying pan on medium-high heat.

When hot, add the carrot and cook until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Once the pork is cooked, remove to a #plate{}, spoon over the honey mustard. Cover with another plate or #foil{} to rest.

Stir the remaining mustard and the @water{100%ml} for the lentils into the frying pan. Bring to the boil, stir in the @chicken stock paste{10%g}, then simmer for ~{2%minutes}.

Stir in the @baby spinach{100%g} in handfuls and cook until wilted and piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}. Once the spinach has wilted, stir in the @creme fraiche{75%g} and lentils.

Bubble away for another ~{1%minute} until everything is piping hot. Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.

Once rested, thinly slice the pork steak widthways.

Pour any resting juices into the lentils and bring back up to the boil until piping hot.

Once piping hot, remove the lentils from the heat and stir through half the parsley.

Spoon the lentils into your #bowls{}. Top with the sliced pork and a sprinkle of the remaining parsley to finish. Enjoy!